<title type="html"><![CDATA[New directory structure for WIki pages]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4540&amp;p=39666#p39666"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">blargg wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Any reason it can't be nesdevwiki.org/Foo ? I always wonder why so many Wikis have seemingly unnecessary cruft between the domain name and the page name (/wiki/ is admittedly minimal).<br /></div><br /><br />The /wiki is actually there for a reason.<br /><br />/wiki/Foo doesn't exist on the server. All the wiki files live in /w/ and the main script is /w/index.php. The webserver rewrites the request to the actual page, which for /wiki/Foo is /w/index.php?title=Foo.<br /><br />The issue with doing a redirect on the top level directory is you have to exclude a lot of files you don't want turned into wiki pages, like robots.txt or favicon.ico, and can run into weird problems if article titles clash with real file.  By using a specific directory, you can rewrite everything.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=134">atarimike</a> — Thu Nov 06, 2008 12:34 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
